In challenges involving multiple layers of base64 encoding, exploit the known redundancy and repetitive patterns of base64 to reverse-engineer a masked message. Base64 encoding converts 6 bits of data into 8 bits, creating redundancy. By brute-forcing characters of the original message to match the encoded string progressively, it's possible to reconstruct the original message. Start by changing the first character until the first encoded character matches, then proceed to subsequent characters, iteratively checking matches by expanding to cover more of the encoded string. Use the following function to automate this process:
   ```python
   def almost_eq(seq, pat):
       return all(s == p or p == '*' for s, p in zip(seq, pat))
   ```

